WHO   — Enheduanna — EN-priestess (high priestess) of the moon-god Nanna at Ur, daughter of Sargon of Akkad, author of the Sumerian Temple Hymns and the Exaltation of Inanna (Nin-me-šara)
WHAT  — EN-priestess (high priestess) of the moon-god Nanna at Ur, daughter of Sargon of Akkad, author of the Sumerian Temple Hymns and the Exaltation of Inanna (Nin-me-šara)
WHERE — AMP · The Greek Mirror — Ur · Sumer (Akkadian Empire)  Framework inputs: the world's philosophers by year and location; the mirror that looks past Greece  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)
WHY   — She is the first author in all of recorded history known by name — and a woman. Her hymns do not merely praise; they reason about the divine, the self, and exile, and sign themselves 'I, Enheduanna.' The mirror seats her first. Honest seam — calling her 'philosopher' stretches the word from its Greek sense toward poet-theologian; that stretch is the point, not a slip.
HOW   — Seated in the Amphitheater of the World's Philosophers, by year and location.

awareness — what the node knows of itself:
  the first author known by name · the first voice of the mirror

